file_name = "russia_201901_1_tweets_csv_hashed.csv"

def boldprint(text):
    """bold the text before printing"""
    return '\033[1m' + text + '\033[0m'

WNL = WordNetLemmatizer()
def preprocess(text):
    """process the text by cleanning, removing and lemmatizing"""
    result = []
    try:
        if text != "":
            if not (text[:4] == "http" and len(text.split()) == 1):
                text = text.translate({ord(c): None for c in string.punctuation+""}).lower()
                for word, tag in pos_tag(word_tokenize(text)):
                    if word not in STOPWORDS and not word.isdigit() and word != "rt":
                        if tag.startswith("NN"):
                            word = WNL.lemmatize(word, pos='n')
                        elif tag.startswith('VB'):
                            word = WNL.lemmatize(word, pos='v')
                        elif tag.startswith('JJ'):
                            word = WNL.lemmatize(word, pos='a')
                        result.append(word)
    except Exception:
        print(Exception)
        print(text)
        return(result)
    return result

2. Data¶

The essay uses data from <Russia (January 2019) - 416 accounts> since Russia is quite active in this kind of issue and its evident expeience may be easy to testify, which may result to supervised modelling in the future.

It is a file with 765246 documents and 30 attributes. They are tweets that are connected to state-backed information operations by Twitter, among which most are retweets, along with retweeted user and corresponding statistics.

Hereby the essay utilizes userid and retweet__userid to build the network and tweet__text to build work2vec modelling, and other attributes are also included to make other regular pattern detection.

def draw_cloud(word_freq):
    """Generate word cloud""" 
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(20, 20))
    mask_img = imageio.imread("twitter.png") # set background photo
    image_colors = ImageColorGenerator(mask_img)
    cloud = WordCloud(collocations=False,
                      max_words=200,
                      background_color='white',
                      mask=mask_img,
                      ).generate_from_frequencies(word_freq)
    plt.imshow(cloud.recolor(color_func=image_colors))
    plt.axis('off')
    plt.show()

draw_cloud(pd.Series(dict(Counter([i for item in all_text for i in item]).most_common())))

2. Networking¶

2.1 Brief Introduction¶

Twitter is a social network, so disinformation in it also spreads by and as network. The data in retweet__userid not only gives the state-backed operated users but also the regular (or not yet identified) ones. To have deeper understanding, I carried some visualizations below.

Around 80% of the nodes in the network only have 1 degree that means this node has only one text that is retweeted or retweeting. Almost all nodes have less than 10 degrees. While there are only a few nodoes hold more than 100 degrees, this phenomenon agrees with the long-tail theory in social network.

The essay finds the connected components in the whole network. It turns out that only 1 component has more than 10 nodes that is 79026 while others are all below 10 and most are 2. So the essay hereby only concerns the largest one, due to lack of knowledge from other components.

2.4 Network Visualization¶

The essay hereby builds the network, shows only nodes with more than 4 degrees, and labels the operated users by +, and conducts community detection to divide it into bisections (two parts).

In [9]:
nodelist = []
node_size = []
for i, j in SG2.degree:
    if j > 4: # larger degree to show graph well
        nodelist.append(i)
        node_size.append(j*4)

SG = nx.OrderedGraph()
SG.add_nodes_from(nodelist)
SG.add_edges_from((u, v) for (u, v) in SG2.edges() if u in SG if v in SG)

# community detection
communities = community.kernighan_lin_bisection(SG, seed=1)
colors = plt.get_cmap("tab20c")(np.arange(len(communities))*4)

# get the two communities respectively
H1 = SG.subgraph(communities[0])
H2 = SG.subgraph(communities[1])
labeled_nodes = [i[0] for i in sorted(H1.degree, key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)[:100]] + \
                [i[0] for i in sorted(H2.degree, key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)[:100]]

plt.figure(figsize=(16, 14)) 
pos = nx.spring_layout(SG, seed=1)
nx.draw(SG, pos = pos,
        nodelist = nodelist, 
        node_size = node_size, 
        node_color = [colors[0] if i in communities[0] else colors[1] for i in nodelist], 
        labels = {i: "+" for i in labeled_nodes if i in users},
        width=0.05, alpha=0.9, font_size=15)
plt.title("Community 1 (0) is Blue, Community 2 (1) is Red", fontsize=22, y=0.93)
plt.show()

The network is divided into two communities, i.e. Community 1 (Blue) and Community 2 (Red), represented by 0/1 in the codes.

Interestingly, the Blue community's operated users are not the ones with the largest influence, while the strongest users in the Red community are all operated users.

If a disinformation organization wants to spread their news, they cannot make all nodes in one community, which leads to no news expanding outside. It is better if they set some strong nodes in the network, but the fake supporters are in other networks, say strong for arousing, ordinary for attracting. From the graph, we can see that these operated users (the trash) are well structured that some act as the storm centers (Red Community) that organize their innocent fans, others act as the disguised civilians, further affecting their pursuit objects and corresponding community.

3.3 Whole Model¶

The essay hereby aggregate all text data to conduct a big Word2Vec model. In below graph, the words related to @realDonaldTrump and @Saminfidel who is an anti-Islam user, are drawed, as well as #trump and _#islam, which are positioned by PCA reflecting to two-dimension.

In [15]:
def plot_pca(names, model, ax):
    show_count = 20    
    words = []
    for name in names:
        words.append(name)
        words.extend([i[0] for i in model.wv.most_similar(name, topn=show_count-1)])
        
    # fit a 2d PCA model to the vectors
    X = model.wv.__getitem__(words)
    pca = PCA(n_components=2)
    result = pca.fit_transform(X)
    ax.scatter(result[:, 0], result[:, 1], facecolors='none', edgecolors='none')

    texts = []
    for index, word in enumerate(words):
        color = int(index / show_count)
        texts.append(ax.text(result[index, 0], result[index, 1], word, 
                            color=plt.cm.Set1(color), label=color))
    ax.set_title(" ".join(names).upper())
    adjust_text(texts, only_move={'points':'y'})

fig, axes = plt.subplots(ncols=2, nrows=1, figsize=[16, 8])
plot_pca(["trump", "islam"], model, axes[0])
plot_pca(["realdonaldtrump", "saminfidel"], model, axes[1])

Clearly showed, words related to Trump, and words related to Islam are quite different from each other. By this Word2Vec method, the essay believe it is possible to build a word detection model detecting all words related to these malicious words, or alarmed words. Once related words, with good similarity, come out with a big quantity, our data protection system should be activated to carry the cleaning.

4. Conclusion¶

The essay analyzes the network of disinformation and its characteristics, in which two different type of operated users are found and hold different operation pattern.

Significantly, Community 1 disguised civilians are fake right-wing or Trump supporters to rally for him, while Communit 2 storm centers are trying to voting for Trump and instigating the hate to Islam.

Furthermore, the essay utilizes Word2Vec to find the different knowledge the two communities have towards different issue. One has more information or attitudes towards its target, but behaves more general towards others.

In the future, for Community 1 disguised civilians, I believe having a big corresponding corpus and building Word2Vec model with it will help detecting more trash words around the issue. With KPI changing monitor (especially for the evident #BUT), the attack will be prevented more. As for Communit 2 storm centers, I think it will be better if we can set alarms on the influential users with more sensitive models, and quickly cutting connections from them to the public.
